<div id="review_213804253" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/213804253" />
    <a title="Nandakishore Mridula" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6237864-nandakishore-mridula"><img alt="Nandakishore Mridula" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1583648733p2/6237864.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/213804253?book_show_action=true">Sep 23, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nandakishore Mridula" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nandakishore Mridula" href="/user/show/6237864-nandakishore-mridula">Nandakishore Mridula</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780451147363" href="/book/show/228162.The_Bachman_Books">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6237864-nandakishore-mridula?shelf=horror">horror</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer213804253" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18165075363385999017">Stephen King created the alter ego of Richard Bachman just to prove that he can make it once again by himself, he says: an enterprise in which he was moderately successful before somebody ferreted out the real identity of this elusive author. (This &quot;multiple personality syndrome&quot; that occurs with writers is explored by King in the story &quot;Secret Window, Secret Garden&quot; and the novel <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11597.The_Dark_Half' title='The Dark Half by Stephen King' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Dark Half</a>.) However, after Bachman was &apos;outed&apos; as Steve King, the sales soared (naturally) and this book was pub</span>
  <span id="freeText18165075363385999017" style="display:none">Stephen King created the alter ego of Richard Bachman just to prove that he can make it once again by himself, he says: an enterprise in which he was moderately successful before somebody ferreted out the real identity of this elusive author. (This "multiple personality syndrome" that occurs with writers is explored by King in the story "Secret Window, Secret Garden" and the novel <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11597.The_Dark_Half" title="The Dark Half by Stephen King" rel="nofollow noopener">The Dark Half</a>.) However, after Bachman was 'outed' as Steve King, the sales soared (naturally) and this book was published, collecting the first four of his short novels.<br /><br />This was a very uneven book for me. The first story, "Rage", where teenagers discover the heady addiction of violence, may be a "significant" story, but left me cold. The third one, "Roadwork", a philosophical look at the slow disintegration of a man, is really well written - but again, not what I expected from Steve! The fourth novella about a future America where violence is a reality show, "The Running Man", was the equivalent of a Hollywood action movie starring any one of the tough guys (it was ultimately made into a movie with Arnold Schwarzenegger, so there!) - very exciting to read but lacking any substance.<br /><br />The one story which elevated this book to three stars for me is the second one, "The Long Walk". This dystopian story is eerie and surrealistic. Once again, it is an ultraconservative future America. One hundred kids take part in a gruelling "walkathon" - only one will come out alive. The others will all fall dead from exhaustion or will be shot by guards following them as they fall behind 4 mph speed thrice within the hour. I absolutely loved this story for its mesmeric atmosphere.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18165075363385999017" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

